</div>
<h3>#5. Keep it short</h3>
When you want to know in detail what your customers feel about your business, it could be tempting to create long surveys that capture maximum information.

Be informed that long surveys can backfire. One of the <strong>best practices</strong> while sending Net Promoter ScoreÂ® response rates surveys is to not let them drown in â€˜survey fatigueâ€™ â€” that sunk feeling while answering long and unending survey questions

If you want users to respond to the survey make a promise that it is a quick and short survey. Also, stick to that promise. You can also hint the same in the subject line â€” <strong><span style="color: #0052cc;">â€˜<a href="https://tour.surveysensum.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Take our quick survey</a>â€™</span></strong>.
<h3>#6. Time it right</h3>
Like social media or even email, even your <a href="https://www.surveysensum.com/blog/net-promoter-score-nps-survey/">Net Promoter ScoreÂ® surveys</a> should be timed right. Donâ€™t jump the gun and send the survey a few hours after they have bought from you.

Give it some time for the user to use to product, get used to it and gauge its utility. Depending on the product or service that you are offering, the sweet spot to send the survey could be from a week to a month.
<h3>#7. Be mobile-friendly</h3>
<strong>56% of emails get read on</strong> iPhones or in Gmail found a <a href="https://litmus.com/blog/email-client-market-share-trends-first-half-of-2018" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Litmus study</a> of emails. What does it mean for your NPSÂ® response rates surveys? They should be mobile-friendly as well.

Users should be able to record their feedback through their mobile devices as well. You can either configure it as an in-app survey or <strong><span style="color: #0052cc;">send a feedback form that</span></strong> goes to an external mobile-friendly site where the feedback can be provided.
<h3>#8. Personalize the thank-you-note</h3>
Net Promoter ScoreÂ® surveys do not end collecting the feedback. If you want your users to respond to your future surveys as well, give them the assurance that their current feedback will be acted upon.

That intention can be easily communicated through the thank-you-note that pops up after the user submits the feedback.

<span style="color: #0052cc;"><strong>In fact</strong></span>, you can create customized responses for promoters, passives, and detractors.
